<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06045234 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06045234 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  EL-SALVADOR; MAN; DISEASE; SURGERY; SAN-JOSE; HOSPITAL  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A seven-hour operation to remove an immense growth from the face of ManuelCerros &quot;went very well,&quot; one of his surgeons, Dr. Seung Kim, said Wednesdayafternoon.;    The operation on Cerros, a 31-year-old Salvadoran with a severeform of the congenital condition called neurofibromatosis, was organized byInterplast, a foundation that provides free plastic surgery for people in theThird World.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SURGERY ON DISFIGURED MAN GOES WELL  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Kim said he and fellow surgeon Vincent Lepore removed nearly all the tumordraping the right half of Cerros' face. They left much of the skin, using itto cover the remaining flesh. They also reduced the size of Cerros' overgrownnose and mouth.;    Cerros was the subject of an article in Tuesday's MercuryNews. Neurofibromatosis is a genetic mutation of nerve cells that can causesymptoms ranging from harmless oversize birthmarks to thousands of small skintumors to legs that look like tree trunks.;    In Cerros' case, the right halfof his face, from hairline to jaw, began swelling when he was born and keptgrowing until his brow, cheek and mouth spilled over and hung down to belowhis chin.;    Despite his disfigurement, Cerros has not been shunned by mostpeople in his community, part of the city of Cojutepeque. He said he believesthat this is because his parents made a point of letting neighbors see him ashe was growing up, so they would be accustomed to his appearance. He knew hewas taking some risks by having the operation but said he hoped that, with amore normal appearance he might get a permanent job, get his driver's licenseand possibly marry.;    A second operation, in about six weeks, will benecessary to reduce the size of his ear and possibly to tighten the side ofhis face.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  DAVID ANSLEY, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Peninsula/PM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910214  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  297  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday February 14, 199100045234,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>